The /var/core directory stores core dump files generated when a process crashes. If multiple dumps from Filebeat appear, it means the Filebeat service is crashing (for example due to a segmentation fault, memory issue, or software bug). When core dumps are enabled (ulimit -c unlimited), the Linux kernel writes a dump file for debugging. To prevent /var/core from filling up, administrators can disable core dumps for Filebeat using systemd (LimitCORE=0), disable them globally via limits.conf, or redirect dumps by changing kernel.core_pattern. It is also recommended to investigate Filebeat logs (journalctl -u filebeat) and implement automatic cleanup or rotation of old core dump files.